In article <bontchev.726254411@fbihh> bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de writes:
> Instead, there are some export -regulations- (which are not
> laws)

Federal regulations have the force of the authorizing United States Code
(i.e., the law) until they are struck down in court.

> My
> guess is that it doesn't and the Department of State keeps the right
> to decide what is crypto software and what isn't.

If the State Department decided that restricting the export of oranges
would be good for world peace, it could add them to the Munitions List,
and U.S. citizens wouldn't be able to export them.

